this is shown SO well in scenes where when jinx goes from believing vi to suddenly wanting to hurt her. it's such a dark trait of bpd but impulsive thoughts like that are extremely common because our brains genuinely believe we are in trouble/under threat and want to protect us

this is where the violent bpd stereotype comes from! borderlines are often sufferers of psychosis + emotional dysregulation. they hear things that aren't there and carry delusions that break them away from reality, such as "my best friend/sibling/parent is going to leave"

it's something not talked about because the people without bpd think of it as 'evil' while the people with bpd believe themselves to be 'bad people' for thinking this way. except patients actually feel intense guilt: they don't really want to manipulate or hurt their loved ones.

it's a struggle that a lot of borderlines deal with. we constantly move between loving our friends and family members and then hating them because we believe they're out to get us or simply don't want to be around us anymore. it can happen over things as simple as missed texts

she is posed as a classic villain while manifesting some of the most negative aspects of bpd that people don't like to talk about/ignore. her moving between fits of idealisation and devaluation ('splitting') is portrayed so hauntingly well.

there are a couple characters who i hc as borderline simply because they exhibit several well-known traits (such as bokuto from haikyu!! or sylvain from fire emblem), but i feel like jinx is such a good example of what childhood trauma and your environment can do to a person
